Frank 'Rocky' Fiegel, born in Poland on January 27, 1868. He emigrated with his family to America where where in 1887 he joined the Navy. When Popeye's creator met him, he was a retired sailor contracted by Wiebusch's tavern in the city of Chester, Illinois, to clean and maintain order. He had a reputation to be always involved in fighting, so he had a deformed eye ("Pop-eye"). He had demonstrated his strength in so many fights that he became a local legend. He always smoked his pipe, so he spoke only with one side of his mouth. When he was with children he held the pipe with the corner of his mouth and told them the antics of his youth, often boasting of his physical strength and loudly claiming that spinach is the food that makes him invincible. Popeye's character creator Elzie Crisler Segar was born in Chester and was one of the children who had the privilege of hearing 'live' the stories of the former sailor.

cleaned_message: ‚ÄúMidday dinner and evening supper were the most prevalent terms in agricultural communities during the 18th and 19th centuries. Farmers would fill up on dinner around noon to carry them through work, but that all started to change when people began working away from the farm and weren't able to return home to eat in the middle of the day, food historian Helen Zoe Veit told NPR. "Supper" became "dinner" because evenings became the only time working class families were able to gather for a meal. In this day and age when someone invites you over to eat, you can safely assume that "lunch" means midday and "dinner" means to arrive in the evening. The word "supper" has faded over the years, but it could be wise to clarify with older generations because being timely is just one of many old-fashioned etiquette lessons your grandma wishes you knew.‚Äù Retvrn to the farm . . . ~ Make Supper Great Again !!

The Charge of the Light Brigade BY ALFRED, LORD TENNYSON I Half a league, half a league, Half a league onward, All in the valley of Death Rode the six hundred. ‚ÄúForward, the Light Brigade! Charge for the guns!‚Äù he said. Into the valley of Death Rode the six hundred. II ‚ÄúForward, the Light Brigade!‚Äù Was there a man dismayed? Not though the soldier knew Someone had blundered. Theirs not to make reply, Theirs not to reason why, Theirs but to do and die. Into the valley of Death Rode the six hundred. III Cannon to right of them, Cannon to left of them, Cannon in front of them Volleyed and thundered; Stormed at with shot and shell, Boldly they rode and well, Into the jaws of Death, Into the mouth of hell Rode the six hundred. IV Flashed all their sabres bare, Flashed as they turned in air Sabring the gunners there, Charging an army, while All the world wondered. Plunged in the battery-smoke Right through the line they broke; Cossack and Russian Reeled from the sabre stroke Shattered and sundered. Then they rode back, but not Not the six hundred. V Cannon to right of them, Cannon to left of them, Cannon behind them Volleyed and thundered; Stormed at with shot and shell, While horse and hero fell. They that had fought so well Came through the jaws of Death, Back from the mouth of hell, All that was left of them, Left of six hundred. VI When can their glory fade? O the wild charge they made! All the world wondered. Honour the charge they made! Honour the Light Brigade, Noble six hundred!

Preparing Livestock for Winter Straw and hay serve all our needs for keeping our animals warm. We have open air wired coops. This is fantastic in the summer for fresh air, sunshine, and livestock health. They're also easy to winterize with stacked straw bale walls. Straw bale walls keep the wind out and the livestock's warmth in. As the weather warms up, we dismantle them and use the straw throughout the homestead. A thick layer of hay or straw on the ground works in much the same way to insulate them‚Äî and also keeps them dry. Tarps ‚Äî tarps work to keep the wind out. But they do not work as insulators. Tarps are a lot less expensive than straw bale walls. Surely rope some tarps up if you don't have bales. "Amazing Grace" is a Christian hymn published in 1779, with words written by the English poet and Anglican clergyman John Newton (1725‚Äì1807). Newton wrote the words from personal experience. He grew up without any particular religious conviction, but his life's path was formed by a variety of twists and coincidences that were often put into motion by his recalcitrant insubordination. He was pressed (conscripted) into service in the Royal Navy, and after leaving the service, he became involved in the Atlantic slave trade. In 1748, a violent storm battered his vessel off the coast of County Donegal, Ireland, so severely that he called out to God for mercy, a moment that marked his spiritual conversion. He continued his slave trading career until 1754 or 1755, when he ended his seafaring altogether and began studying Christian theology. Amazing grace! How sweet the sound That saved a wretch like me! I once was lost, but now am found; Was blind, but now I see. ‚ÄôTwas grace that taught my heart to fear, And grace my fears relieved; How precious did that grace appear The hour I first believed. Through many dangers, toils and snares, I have already come; ‚ÄôTis grace hath brought me safe thus far, And grace will lead me home. The Lord has promised good to me, His Word my hope secures; He will my Shield and Portion be, As long as life endures. Yea, when this flesh and heart shall fail, And mortal life shall cease, I shall possess, within the veil, A life of joy and peace. The earth shall soon dissolve like snow, The sun forbear to shine; But God, who called me here below, Will be forever mine. Admin 2 here: I just finished Matt Walsh's documentary "What Is A Woman?". As an up-front, unqualified position, I love it and it ought to be shared everywhere. I do take issue with his definition. Woman is not an "Adult Human Female". To be clear here, Walsh knows better. He is an intelligent Roman Catholic who, from all indications I have seen, know his Church's teachings on men and women. His definition is decidedly naturalistic and Godless. He stresses over and over, and even agrees with Dr Phil's characterization of a woman's identity being rooted in biology. He knows better but doesn't advocate for a real definition. This isn't a matter of pedantry for me, despite how this might be taken. The Scriptures are very clear about what a woman is (Gen2:18; 1Cor11:7,9; Eph5:29-32). There are two genders, man and woman. They were each made for a purpose--that is, they each have a telos. A woman is, not what her biology is, but what she was made for, and what her biology, psychology, and spirit confess to by their very existence. A woman is a human made to model femininity. She was made to model the Church who submits to Christ. She was made to model growth, nurture, possibility, and beauty. She was made to bring forth life and be the Glory of man. Womanhood is grounded in those things, not in biology. A woman's biology is only one expression of that Telos. To reduce womanhood to that is to fall into the same naturalist mindset we want to be rid of.

url_title: The Stingray: How Law Enforcement Can Track Your Every Move
url_description: RALEIGH, North Carolina (WTVD) -- You could be just about anywhere and data on your cell phone can be scooped up by law enforcement without your ever knowing. It happens all the time. The device that makes it possible is called a "cell site simulator." That's the generic name; Stingray is the most common brand name. Initially developed for military use, Stingrays have made their way into local police and sheriff's departments around the country. Months ago, the I-Team sent open records requests to every law enforcement agency in our viewing area and learned that three agencies close to home have been using cell site simulators: the Wake County Sheriff's Department, Durham Police Department, and Raleigh Police Department. A spokesperson for RPD told the I-Team they stopped using theirs when the software needed to be upgraded. The ACLU's Mike Meno has been watching Stingrays spread into local law enforcement for years. "Like a lot of militarized technology and surveillance technology, this is something that was developed overseas and it was developed for one use, but then it comes back home and is used against our own citizens. It's used here in the States. And the government will say, 'We need to keep this confidential,' but we have constitutional rights. We're supposed to have checks and balances," he said. http://abc11.com/1968769/

At 40, Franz Kafka (1883-1924), who never married and had no children, was walking through a park one day in Berlin when he met a girl who was crying because she had lost her favourite doll. She and Kafka searched for the doll unsuccessfully. Kafka told her to meet him there the next day and they would come back to look for her. The next day, when they had not yet found the doll, Kafka gave the girl a letter "written" by the doll saying "please don't cry. I took a trip to see the world. I will write to you about my adventures." Thus began a story which continued until the end of Kafka's life. During their meetings, Kafka read the letters of the doll carefully written with adventures and conversations that the girl found adorable. Finally, Kafka brought back the doll (he bought one) that had returned to Berlin. "It doesn't look like my doll at all," said the girl. Kafka handed her another letter in which the doll wrote: "my travels have changed me." The little girl hugged the new doll and brought the doll with her to her happy home. A year later Kafka died. Many years later, the now-adult girl found a letter inside the doll. In the tiny letter signed by Kafka it was written: "Everything you love will probably be lost, but in the end, love will return in another way." Embrace change. It's inevitable for growth. Together we can shift pain into wonder and love, but it is up to us to consciously and intentionally create that connection.

He is acting o'er the battles, With his cap and feather gay, Singing out his soldier prattle, In a mocking manly way‚Äî With the boldest, bravest footstep, Treading firmly up and down, And his banner waving softly, O'er his boyish locks of brown. And I sit beside him sewing, With a busy heart and hand, For the gallant soldier's going To the far-off battle land‚Äî And I gaze upon my jewel, In his baby spirit bold, My little blue-eyed soldier, Just a second summer old. Still deep, deep well of feeling In my mother's heart is stirred, And the tears come softly stealing At each imitative word! There's a struggle in my bosom, For I love my darling boy‚Äî He's the gladness of my-spirit, He's the sunlight of my joy! Yet I think upon my country, And my spirit groweth bold‚Äî O! I wish my blue-eyed soldier Were but twenty summers old! I would speed him to the battle‚Äî I would arm him for the fight; I would give him to his country, For his country's wrong and right! I would nerve his hand with blessing From the "God of Battles" won‚Äî With His helmet, and His armor, I would cover o'er my son! O! I know there'd be a struggle, For I love my darling boy; He's the gladness of my spirit, He's the sunlight of my joy! Yet, in thinking on my country, O! my spirit groweth bold! url_description: Your tour of Lerwick Up Helly Aa 2019, in just 4 minutes. Europe‚Äôs largest fire festival, nearly a century and a half in the making, Inherited and created by generations of Shetlanders. Up Helly Aa is a superb spectacle, a celebration of Shetland history, and a triumphant demonstration of islanders' skills, spirit and community. It takes several thousand people 364 days to organise. Much of the preparation is in strictest secrecy. The biggest secret of all is what the head of the festival, the 'Guizer Jarl', will wear and which character from the Norse Sagas he'll represent in each of the 12 Shetland fire festivals held between January and March each year. Lerwick Up Helly Aa is the largest of our fire festivals, with around 1,000 guizers taking part in the evening procession. On May 16, 1771 North Carolina militia under the command of North Carolina planter, Capt. Benjamin Merrill engaged the British Army in the ultimate battle of the Regulator Rebellion. Members of all North Carolina's main demographics united in opposition to mounting royal taxation of American industry and corrupt judicial practices. The feelings that underpinned the Regulator War were not alleviated though. Reeling under oppressive excise taxes, crown monopolies, and official corruption-- North Carolina was among the first states to form Committees of Public Vigilance and on May 11, 1775 delegates to the colonial assembly passed Mecklenburg Resolves, making North Carolina the first British North American colony to declare independence.

One of the earliest and most famous examples of the bull's prominence can be found in the Minoan civilization on the island of Crete. The Minoans, who flourished from around 3000 to 1100 BCE, worshipped a bull-headed deity known as the Minotaur. This half-man, half-bull figure is believed to have represented both the power of nature and the primal instincts of humanity. The Minoan civilization considered the bull sacred and incorporated it into their religious rituals and iconography. The influence of the Minoans extended to mainland Greece, where the bull's importance continued to be recognized. In Greek mythology, the god Zeus, the king of the gods, was often depicted in the form of a bull. One of his most famous exploits involved transforming into a white bull to carry off the princess Europa. This myth symbolized Zeus's power, allure, and connection to fertility.

The bull's association with these powerful deities highlights its role in the divine hierarchy and its connection to the forces of nature.

When the semi-mythical figure Lycurgus came up with the concept of Agoge, his goal was to mold the Spartan citizen into a warrior who could endure any circumstances that might befall him. Because of this, during the period of Agoge, the boys would never be fully satiated and would only have one cloak for the entire year. Similarly, the boys were instructed to walk barefoot, bathe exclusively in cold rivers compared to hot baths and they were instructed to speak only when spoken to. As such Xenophon states that the boys would walk around Sparta with a low gaze in total silence, looking at the ground, head covered in their cloak. This would manifest itself spectacularly on the battlefield by the fact that the army would march in perfect formation in silence to the rhythm of the music. As one could expect, this would have a massive psychological effect on their enemies. We are bringing back The Agoge on the 14th of July at 18:00 CET.

When most people think of Sparta the first thing that comes to mind is military prowess. It is obvious why that is the case, but what most people do not understand is that this military prowess didn‚Äôt come out of nowhere. After all, the Spartans were humans like any others on the planet, they didn‚Äôt possess some extraordinary and built-on qualities other people did not have, especially their fellow Helens as Herodotus would put it, and yet despite this at one point Sparta held dominance among the entire Peloponnese. What the Spartans lacked in their biology they made up for in their education which was based on self-induced adversity. This adversity came in the form of The Agoge. And yet, The Agoge was not centered just on physical betterment but overall character development, after all, Plutarch states that The Agoge was a school of obedience.

Moreover, the martial aspect of Mithraism is thought to have resonated with the soldiers' desires for protection and success in battle. Mithras was often associated with solar symbolism and was believed to possess the power to safeguard his followers in their military endeavors. The cult offered a sense of brotherhood and promised divine assistance to its members, making it an attractive spiritual option for those engaged in the dangerous and uncertain world of warfare. While the Cult of Mithras did attract followers from various social backgrounds, its connection to the military and its emphasis on martial virtues made it particularly appealing to soldiers. The cult provided a sense of community, spiritual purpose, and the hope for divine favor in the challenging and often brutal context of Roman military life. Although mystery cults in the late Roman Empire were anything but uncommon, the Cult of Mithras was inherently unique by the fact that its members were all male of whom most were soldiers, indicating that the cult appealed to the common soldier. The cult's emphasis on hierarchy, discipline, and the pursuit of spiritual enlightenment through a series of initiations likely appealed to Roman soldiers. The military context of the Roman Empire often encouraged a strict chain of command and a strong sense of duty and loyalty. The Cult of Mithras provided a parallel structure of ranks and levels, creating a familiar framework for its adherents.

In ancient Greek mythology, the dragon was associated with the primordial deities, such as Typhon and Python, who embodied chaos and represented the untamed forces of nature. In Norse mythology, dragons played a central role, with the great serpent Jormungandr encircling the world, and the dragon Fafnir guarding a cursed treasure. In Christian mythos, the dragon took on a more malevolent role, often associated with Satan or the Devil. The biblical Book of Revelation depicts a great red dragon representing evil and opposing the forces of good. This association persisted throughout the Middle Ages when dragons were commonly portrayed as adversaries of Christian heroes, such as Saint George. And yet despite this, The Dragon remained one of the most predominantly used symbols in medieval heraldry. This was especially the case in The House of DrƒÉcule»ôti. The father of Vlad III Tepes, Vlad II acquired the sobriquet Dracul (Dragon in medieval Romanian) because of his position in the Order of the Dragon. Vlad the Third Impaler adopted his father's sobriquet but modified it to Dracula meaning in a Slavonic genitive form ‚Äú(the son) of the Dracul‚Äù (meaning; of the Dragon). The interesting thing is that Dracul in Romanian means ‚ÄúThe Devil‚Äù which would make Dracula translate also as ‚ÄúThe son of the Devil‚Äù Vlad himself signed important documentation as "Dragulya" or "Drakulya" in the late 1470s.

The Dragon appears as one of the most prominent symbols of European medieval heraldry as well as mythology, captivating the human imagination for centuries; therefore it is no surprise to see the symbolism of the dragon being used in many medieval families and chivalric orders. In mythology the dragon represents a primordial force, embodying both the destructive and transformative powers of nature. As such, it is often depicted as a fearsome and powerful being, capable of wreaking havoc or granting blessings.

cleaned_message: One of the most prominent and most apparent forms of moral truisms is the notion that positivity and as a result the state of being positive equates to something which is ‚Äúgood‚Äù while negativity and the state of being native (or oftentimes just real) equates to something which is ‚Äúbad‚Äù This phenomenon is most apparent with clich√© slogans like ‚Äúlive, love and laugh‚Äù, ‚Äúdon‚Äôt worry, be happy‚Äù, and ‚Äújust think positive‚Äù along with the excessive need to appear happy and smile all the time, even when the topic or the person in question is anything but happy and positive. No matter what is being talked about, no matter how serious the issue at hand might be, and no matter what is being presented, it always has to come off as inherently positive. Although this might sound appealing on the surface, this excessive focus on positivity is anything but positive, more than anything, it is a form of escapism because it doesn‚Äôt coincide with reality. People aren‚Äôt naturally happy all the time and people aren‚Äôt naturally positive all the time. A person who is devoid of all emotions outside of happiness is at worst clinically insane or at the very best, heavily sedated and/or intoxicated. Therefore this excessive need to appear positive and happy is an incredibly fake and cheap marketing tactic utilized to sell a product, but to make it even worse, by fixating on this idea that everything should be positive we inevitably create a false sense of reality which can be extremely dangerous when the inevitable negative things in life happen as we simply won‚Äôt be adapted to endure the trials and tribulations we are presented with. While our goal is to spread a positive message, we don‚Äôt aim to do so at the expense of reality. Therefore Legion Wear is a toxic positivity-free zone. Positivity is not a state we can habitually stay in. Positivity is a product of overcoming adversity.

A moral-truism is defined as a certain outlook that is taken for granted and viewed as objectively correct, but yet rarely subjected to thorough analysis. It resembles a mantra mindlessly repeated, devoid of true understanding.

A drengr is a fearless warrior who is willing to take on any challenge, no matter how daunting or dangerous. One of the key elements of Lupercalia was the Luperci, a group of young men who were responsible for carrying out the rituals of the festival. The Luperci would begin the festival by sacrificing a goat and a dog, which were believed to represent fertility and purification. After the sacrifices, the Luperci would cut strips of the goat's hide into thongs, or strips, and run through the streets of Rome, striking anyone they encountered with the thongs. This act of striking was believed to bring fertility and good luck to those who were hit. Women, in particular, would often offer their hands to the Luperci to be struck with the thongs, as it was believed to increase their chances of conceiving. This tradition eventually evolved into a more playful activity, where men would draw the names of women from a lottery and pair off with them for the duration of the festival. In addition to the thong striking, Lupercalia was also a time for feasting and gift-giving. It was customary for people to exchange small gifts, such as flowers and sweets, as well as to enjoy a large feast together. The holiday was also a time for people to visit the temples of the gods and offer prayers and sacrifices. Lupercalia continued to be celebrated in Rome until the 5th century AD when it was eventually replaced by the Christian holiday of St. Valentine's Day.

February 15th marks one of the most important dates for the ancient Roman religion, as it was the date of the Roman festival Lupercalia. It was a festival that was dedicated to the god of fertility, Lupercus, as well as the Roman founders, Romulus and Remus, and their she-wolf ‚Äúmother‚Äù. The holiday had both religious and cultural significance, and it was a time for feasting, gift-giving, and fertility rituals.

Julian was a well-educated man who was deeply influenced by the ideas of Greek philosophy, particularly Neoplatonism. He saw the traditional Roman religion as a more rational and humane system of beliefs, in contrast to the strict monotheism of Christianity. During his reign, Julian made significant changes to the administration and religious practices of the empire. He sought to limit the power of the Christian Church, promote the worship of the old gods, and restore the ancient customs and traditions of Rome. He sought to return the Empire to its golden years by viewing himself as primus inter pares ("first among equals"), operating under the same laws as his subjects. Unlike some of his pagan predecessors, Julian did not partake in anti-Christian prosecutions but instead aimed on returning the Empire to the form it once had, particularly by passing an edict proclaiming the freedom of religion, at which all religions were equal under the law, and pioneering the return to original religious eclecticism, to which the Roman state did not impose any religion on its provinces. Similarly, Julian successfully reopened vast sums of pagan temples, returned from exile ‚Äúheretical‚Äù Christian bishops as well as allowed the Jews to rebuild the Third Temple in Jerusalem. Julian's popularity among the populace and the army during his brief reign suggests that he may have reintroduced paganism into Roman public and private life. Neither pagan nor Christian ideology reigned supreme during his lifetime, and the greatest thinkers of the time debated the merits and rationality of each religion.

In the year 313 AD Emperor Constantine issued the Edict of Milan, which proclaimed Christianity as an accepted religion in the Roman Empire, 10 years later it would become the official religion of the Empire. But Rome was not out of pagan emperors. In the year 361 AD Rome would get its last Pagan emperor, Flavius Claudius Julianus, also known as Julian the Apostate. Julian was a man of contradictions, a philosopher who took up arms, and a pagan who rose to power in a Christian world.

in certain parts of Britain, the hunt is said to be that of hell-hounds chasing sinners or the unbaptized led by the Archangel Gabriel himself. How much all of these cultural events are tied up (by the greater unconscious as Jung would say) is the fact that the Wild Hunt is heavily intertwined with the original Celtic festival of Samhain. A very interesting nod is that the role of the Wild Hunt had probably to a large extent influenced the role of Saint Nicholas, and therefore Santa Claus. And potentially from that link, we can track the Old Western ‚ÄúRiders in the Sky‚Äù (mostly known because of the performance of the musical legend Johnny Cash) as that song depicts a band of demons and hellhounds led by the Devil himself. ‚ÄúTheir brands were still on fire And their hooves were made of steel Their horns were black and shiny And their hot breath he could feel‚Äù

The concept of the Wild Hunt was popularized by the German linguist/folklorist Jacob Ludwig Karl Grimm. In his treatise called ‚ÄúDeutsche Mythologie‚Äù Karl argues that the group of stories that loosely depict on what is today known as the Wild Hunt is the remnants of the ancient Germanic pre-Christian tradition. Although this is probably correct, it stands interesting the fact how much the concept of the Wild Hunt is present outside of the Germanic world, and how much the interpretation can be different from one place to another. The most popular depiction of the Wild Hunt is that the ancient Norse/Germanic God Odin is in charge of the procession. And even more fascinating is how in certain scenarios the depiction of the Wild Hunt is positive, and in others, it is highly negative.

After a major military victory, the triumphant military generals were paraded through the streets to the roars of the masses. The ceremonial procession could span the course of a day with the military leader riding in a chariot drawn by four horses. There was not a more coveted honor. The general was idolized, viewed as divine by his troops and the public alike. But riding in the same chariot, standing just behind the worshiped general, was a slave. The slave‚Äôs sole responsibility for the entirety of the procession was to whisper in the general‚Äôs ear continuously, ‚ÄúRespice post te. Hominem te esse memento. Memento mori!‚Äù ‚ÄúLook behind. Remember thou art mortal. Remember you must die!‚Äù Contemporary view of Memento Mori is very bleak. A somber reminder of the fragility of existence itself. But this is far from the truth, and diametrically opposed to how we view it. In reality Memento Mori is an incredibly positive statement, by saying this we acknowledge that today is not the date. Today we are alive. And what an amazing circumstance that is. The clock is ticking, and this could be your last hour. What have you done with your life up until this moment if it is supposed to be your last? If the answer is not good than act upon it.

Memento Mori - Latin for remember that you [have to] die/remember about your death. Seneca wrote in Moral Letters to Lucilius "Let us prepare our minds as if we‚Äôd come to the very end of life. Let us postpone nothing. Let us balance life‚Äôs books each day‚Ä¶The one who puts the finishing touches on their life each day is never short of time" Similarly, in Meditations, Marcus Aurelius wrote: (to himself) "You could leave life right now. Let that determine what you do and say and think" Although the concept of Memento Mori has been present since classical antiquity, it is believed the modern concept originates from the Roman Republic.

During a discussion between the two men, Dionysius offered to switch places with Damocles for one day so that Damocles could experience all the ‚Äúpleasures‚Äù that his position brought. Damocles eagerly accepted the proposal. As such Damocles sat on Dionysius‚Äôs throne and as a result received all of the benefits a ruler gets. There were beautifully embroidered rugs and the most select of foods, piles of silver and gold, and the service of attendants unparalleled in their beauty, surrounding Damocles with riches and excess. While it seemed perfect on the surface the pleasure came with a cost. Dionysius arranged that a sword should hang above the throne, held at the pommel only by a single hair of a horse's tail to evoke the sense of what it is like to be king: unprecedented responsibility and danger. Damocles finally begged the king that he be allowed to depart because he no longer wanted to be so fortunate, knowing what is the cost of success. Essentially, the Sword of Damocles is a quintessential paradigm of success, power and strength. Everyone wants more success, power and strength but very few are willing to embark on that path due to the obvious challenges and tribulations that path brings. Therefore it is easy to conclude that it is much easier to walk the path of mediocrity and weakness as that path requires no strength and responsibility. But on the contrary, it takes a tremendous amount of strength to willingly take on and accept the trials and tribulations the path of success, power and strength brings. Therefore everyone has to make a choice. Live your life like a coward and avoid any and all possible uncertainties or take on your Sword of Damocles willingly and live your life heroically.

Looking at it from a surface level, Dionysius had everything a man could ever desire. He was surrounded by luxury, pleasures and wealth, yet in spite of that Dionysius seemed extremely miserable. This was something Damocles could not comprehend.

The Marian reforms were a military reorganization conducted by Gaius Marius in the ancient Roman Republic. They came out of necessity due to the military and logistical stagnation of the Roman Republic in the late 2nd century BC. These reforms would reshape the Roman army into the legion we normally associate it with today, and likewise they would pave the way for Roman conquest and the inevitable transition in the Roman Empire. The structural organization was established as such: All soldiers fell int one of two categories. - The Legionary (A Roman citizen) - An Auxiliary (Non Roman citizen) - Legionaries join an infantry unit consisting of 8 men. This unit is called a contubernium. - 10 contubernium form a century (80 men). A century has it's own Signifier, Tesserarius, Optio as well as a Centurion who is main in command. - 6 Centuries (480 men + Centurians) form a Cohort. - 10 Cohorts + a small cavalry unit The Equites Legionis (120 riders) make up the biggest Roman army unit, the Legion.

The Decline of the West (German: Der Untergang des Abendlandes) written by the German historian and philosopher Oswald Spengler elevates itself as one of the most important philosophical works of the 20th century. In the book, Oswald proposes a new theory for the outlook of world history which up until that point was limited to the linear time-frame of existence. That is, most historians and philosophers argued that history revolves on a linear-time frame. In Eurocentric circles that would be the ancient-medieval-modern time frame. Instead, Oswald proposed an outlook which presented the idea that cultures develop independently as living organisms and, in those cultures, (and afterwards; civilizations) time exists on a cyclical time-frame Spengler believed that cultures flourish for a thousand years and decline for a thousand years. Due to his immense fascination with the German poet Johann Wolfgang von Goethe, Spengler used Goethe‚Äôs metaphor of seasons to describe the cyclical lifespan of each culture

Similarly, if the offended party did not come to the Holmgang they would have been considered a "ni√∞ingr", basically a social stigma for an individual who had no honor, and therefore a villain cast out of the tribal system. This was often times in reality a death sentence. A similar term would be ergi, which would mean something in the likes of "unmanly" If someone was unwilling or unable to defend their claim, they had no honor. A 13th-century document from V√§sterg√∂tland, Sweden documents some parts of the Holmgang which states: "If someone speaks insults to another man ("You're not the like of a man, and not a man in your chest!" ‚Äì "I‚Äôm a man like you!"), they shall meet where three roads meet. If he who has spoken comes and not the insulted one, then he shall be as he's been called: no right to swear oaths, no right to bear witness, may it concern man or woman If the insulted one comes and not he who has spoken, then he shall cry "Ni√∞ingr!" three times and make a mark in the ground, and he is worse who spoke what he dared not keep" As we can see, the stakes were very high in ancient Scandinavia, and honor played a huge role in the function of society. Running one's mouth could land one with a severed head. The original Acta Non Verba.

Holmgang or h√≥lmganga in Old Norse was a legally recognized way of settling disputes through duels. The place of a duel was normally a small island (In Old Norse holmr) from which we can speculate the name Holmgang originates. The duel could have been conducted for a variety of reasons, ranging from legal disputes, debt, avenging a friend or similarly common, protecting one's honor. An interesting situation was that (in theory) anyone could challenge anyone regardless of the social status. Therefore, everyone had to be very careful on how they acted and behaved as no one was exempt from this system. From this we can conclude that honor was an extremely important factor in ancient Scandinavia, so much so that death was a more favorable outcome than being labeled as honorless. If the person who was challenged did not show up for the Holmgang, the other side was considered right in their cause and therefore legally on the winning side.

The most popular depiction of the Wild Hunt is that the ancient Norse/Germanic God Odin is in charge of the procession. And even more fascinating is how in certain scenarios the depiction of the Wild Hunt is positive, and in others it is highly negative. in certain parts of Britain, the hunt is said to be that of hell-hounds chasing sinners or the unbaptized led by the Archangel Gabriel himself. Whilst in others it is the Devil who is in charge of the pack. How much all of these cultural events are tied-up (by the greater unconscious as Jung would say) is the fact that the Wild Hunt is heavily intertwined by the originally Celtic festival of Samhain. A very interesting nod is that the role of the Wild Hunt had probably in a large extent influenced the role of Saint Nicholas, and therefore Santa Claus. And potentially from that link we can track the Old Western ‚ÄúRiders in the Sky‚Äù (mostly known because of the performance of the musical legend Johnny Cash) as that song depicts a band of demons and hellhounds led by the Devil himself. ‚ÄúTheir brands were still on fire And their hooves were made of steel Their horns were black and shiny And their hot breath he could feel‚Äù

The concept of the Wild Hunt was popularized by the German linguist/folklorist Jacob Ludwig Karl Grimm. In his treatise called ‚ÄúDeutsche Mythologie‚Äù Karl argues that the group of stories that loosely depict on what is today known as the Wild Hunt is the remnants of the ancient Germanic pre-Christian tradition. Although this is probably correct, it stands interesting the fact how much the concept of the Wild Hunt is present outside of the Germanic world, and how much the interpretation can be different from one place to another.

As one customer questions why "the current cost of 18k gold is 42 euro/gram. The ring I believe is 9 grams which is 380 euro. The ring is offered for 88.14 euro in silver. Why is the cost so much higher other than the cost of the material?" I decided to give him a detailed explanation as I felt a little bit offended by the question but after all everyone decides how to spend their hard earned money. So anyway I spent time to explain and decided to share it also here as someone else may be interested: "The craftsmens has a rule - they never question why something costs what it cost. It is not a proper manner to ask this. Anyway, I will try to explain to you: 1. Wood cost 20 euros but the woodcarving made of machine cost 200 euros at least. Sometimes 300, even 500. 10 times higher. 2. The ring is more than 9 grams. 8-9 grams is the silver one. Gold is heavier. 3. There are losses of gold during the finishing process. That means it requires more gold than you will receive and this gold is lost. Also investments in machines and etc. 4. There is "intellectual property". By that, I mean that this model is made entirely by our modelist. Also, there is a photographer which brings you nice photos, to look like European work. Also, there is website maintenance. We made this website 6-8 months without earning even a single cent from it. 5. You can check another store whats their price of 18k yellow gold rings with an approximate weight of 12 grams. We can also add that there are no such NS stores amongst them I believe (I could be wrong). "
